Ra's first nest: 3rd & only fertile egg of 4 egg clutch on Anchor in 2016. Hatched in Incubator & transferred to Toitiiti's nest at 3 days, swapped to Jem's nest at 25 days. comments: Flossie’s second chick (3rd egg) hatched and raised by Jean for 8 days then transferred to Heather’s nest with Heather’s similar size/age chick until 27 days when it was removed for hand-rearing due to a respiratory problem and sudden weight loss.  The 2 chicks' identities were mixed up while together in Heather's nest and as a result the DNA blood labels were misslabled as Hea-2009-2 for Scratxch and Flo-2009-3 for Guapo.  Named Oscar as a chick as he was carried to the hut in a bucket and grumbled all the way home (Oscar the grouch).  His name was changed to Scratch in January 2010 keeping the theme of a stroppy and stubborn chick, in recognition of the significant contributions to the kakapo recovery programme made by Paul Jansen, aka Scratch. Although Paul got worn down and frustrated and was/still is at times unreasonable, it does not detract from the significant vision and advances he made within the programme. He picked the programme up at a vulnerable time just after a big international based review and moved it ahead despite a range of difficulties at that time. He brought together a disjointed programme across three Conservancies and made them into a team, scored significant resources. Responsible for developing some of the technology (in conjunction with others on the team) that are now seen as everyday equipment; nest monitors and cameras (with rat bangers prior to kiore eradication), snarks, heat pads etc The programme would not be where it is today without his personal sacrifice, committment and determination to succeed and as such deserves to be recognised within the programme.  Named by Graeme Elliott.

She returned to the Whenua Hou pen, but gradually lost weight so the release was delayed. Hand feeding was reinstated in early November to increase her weight, but she aspirated a little food and was returned to  NZCCM after 11.5 weeks (aged 271 days). She received a further 82 days of treatment and recovery for pneumonia. Finally returning to Whenua Hou at 353 days and released from the Obs Rock Pen 3 days later. Named Koru for her first birthday by Claire Cameron (NZCCM), meaning new life, growth, and peace - a sweet gentle chick; also a nod to AirNZ for all their transport of ill kakapo this year. Jean's 2nd egg of 3. Hatched and reared by Jean.  Chick ID name = J1 changed to Blake in honor of Sir Peter Blake. Died on 28/11/17, 2.80kg after being handled for annual tx change. Hot weather for Anchor Island ~25 deg C, 40 minute chase, 15 minutes in bag (struggling and vocal) and 40 minute handling time. Struggled and panted a lot, then over-heated and colapsed. Died soon afterward. DIAGNOSIS Probable heat stress. DIAGNOSIS
Probable heat stress. COMMENTS Given the history and acute nature of Blake's death, heat stress seems the most likely cause of death. Within the cardiac, skeletal and smooth muscle (the gizzard in this instance) there was evidence of contraction band formation within the muscle fibers; this can occur with elevated levels of catelcholamine (adrenaline and noradrenaline) from the adrenal glands as a result of acute stress. There was no obvious indication of a apture-type myopathy, or evidence that he had regurgitated/aspirated; he was in good body condition with no obvious evidence of any underlying disease. No bacteria (including Erysipelothrix) were isolated from the liver and no Salmnonella was found in the faeces (nor were any coccidia or helminths).

description: 11/04/09: Missing tip and claw; from male attack as a 2 week old nestling
comments: Fuchsia's only (2nd) chick of 2 eggs. He hatched in Fuchsia’s nest at 9pm during a sustained period of very strong winds on Whenua Hou, at which time the tent was being buffeted and the fly was being ripped from its moorings, hence the name Bluster. At 14 days old, he was attacked in the nest by an adult kakapo, Arab, leaving him with a missing toe on each foot and two serious wounds on his body and head. At Invercargill resident vet Joanne Paul-Murphy performed surgery on his wounds and saved his life. Hence the last name Murphy in recognition of the amazing work that Joanne performed on Bluster and other chicks in the 2009 season. The dual name, Bluster (Two Toes) Murphy (named by Errol Nye) gives him a very strong sounding toughman name fitting of the kakapo that survived an attack, and like Arab, has the scars to prove it.

Referred to as Bella 1 throughout hand-rearing, until January 2010.  According to early Maori knowledge:  At night, the birds come forth and collected at their Whawharua, which is a common meeting place or play ground for all birds which belong to that particular tribe......Having collected, every bird, with one exception goes through a strange performance, by beating it's wings on the ground uttering its weird cry, at the same time forming a hole in the ground with its beak.  Each Whawharua has its leader, which is known as the Tiaka.  During the above performance the Tiaka keeps walking around the whawharua, presumably acting as a sentry, it does not join in the picnic.  At dawn the Tiaka leads the flock back to their hiding places.  This Tiaka is said to have been always a small bird (a female) this bird would become the leader of the future whawharua of kakapo. Named by Deidre Vercoe.

Sex determined by GBS/DNA test results 7/4/19. Huhana's second egg of a four egg clutch in 2019. Egg and chick name Huhana-2-A-19. She hatched in an incubator and was hand-reared for 3 days before returning to her mother's nest until 34 days of age when she was fostered to Hoki's nest already containing Bella-1-A-19 and Tuarua.  At 47 days she was transferred to Weheruatanga-o-te-po's nest after Hoki became terminally ill with aspergillosis.  However, at fledgling age (78 days) she was sent to NZCCM (Auckland Zoo) for aspergillosis diagnosis and extended treatment as the reason for Hoki and Bella-1-A deaths became known. Waa-A1-2022 was named Tuterakipaua by Michael Skerrett (iwi). Named for one of Michael's ancestors. Tuterakipaua a son of Michael's great great great  grandparents Pokene and Hinetaumai.
 
"He was a brother to my great great grandmother Titapu, her son Te Here was named after his uncle Tuterakipaua. That was an interesting thing and it took a bit of thinking how the names related to one another. Then the penny dropped, herehere is the term for prisoner and Tuterakipaua was taken prisoner. Te Here is my great grandfather and his name probably got shortened from Te Herehere when talking casually. Just like James gets shortened to Jim. Te Here was quite a significant person down here in his day. After his mother died he was raised on Ruapuke. His wife was Waa’s daughter, Kurukuru/Dorcas Honor. On Waa’s death Kurukuru’s younger brother Kaiporohu Bragg was sent to Ruapuke. Te Here and Kaiporohu did many things together, They pioneered the commercial oyster fishery, They built the original wharf at half Moon Bay, and they charted the Oreti/Waihopai Estuary for the sailing ships. When the ships couldn’t get up to the Invercargill wharf because of silting they would ferry the freight from down towards the mouth of the estuary. There is a lot of information about Te Here in the Rakiura Museum, He did some mid-wife work and a trustee for the school. In one publication I read it said he was the smartest man on Rakiura."
Name is Tomua (to be early) in recognition of the very early kakapo season of 2019.

Solstice was the first kakapo to receive artificial insemination by Juan Blanco and he named her Ra "the Sun". The winter Solstice is the beginning of bringing the power of the Sun back to land, the Sun for all cultures is the one fertilizing the Mother earth. However, fertilization of earth cannot be made without the concourse of the water (oceans) as the element that finally brings life to all that exists on earth. It is basically the union of the Sun and the water what produced the miracle of life. After mating with Felix, Solstice was inseminated with sperm from Smoko, Stumpy and Arab; Smoko is Ra’s father.

Died soon after about 50 small trees recently planted within his home range had been sprayed with organo-phosphate insecticides and snail baits had been placed around these plants. Supplementary fed male, alone on Mana; recent decrease of appetite noted shortly before death. Had been booming all winter, 1.7kg at death. Diagnosis: 1 - Recent focal hepatic necrosis & difuse fatty liver change; 2 - Hyperplastic spleen; 3- Terminal aspiration of crop contents. Moderate autolysis. Lessions of the liver & spleen support the possibility of septicaemia. The lessions are not indicative of any specific toxic substance although the possibility cannot be ruled out. Display mount in Te Papa Museum, Wellington, green plumage.

Atareta-A2-2022 was named Pukaea by ranger Sarah Manktelow. A Pukaea is a large trumpet instrument. It was traditionally made using some native hard wood, such as Matai. It was once used by Maori for various signalling purposes, including to welcome people and to make important announcements, as well as for use in war. Both of Atareta's chicks were noted to be quite vocal so the reference to an instrument that makes loud noises is quite fitting! The name could be shortened to 'kaea', which means 'to lead' or 'to wander/roam' - very fitting for Atareta-A2-2022 who lost his transmitter soon after fledging and was relocated by pure luck having wandered down to the South West corner of Anchor!

First egg of Hine Taumai's 3 egg clutch on Anchor in 2016. Hatched in Hine Taumai's nest, first seen on 21/2/16 19:00. With Hine Taumai for 11 d, then to Maram's nest until 14 d and to Mila for 1 d.  Mila failed to feed her, so was removed for Hand-rearing, initially on Anchor, then at Invercargill. Released on Anchor after weaning. Named by Michael Skerrett, the chairman of Kaitiaki Ropu o Murihiku, after his Ngai Tahu ancestor Titapu, the daughter of Hine Taumai.
No visible fertility. Egg frozen whole for future examination via microscopy.

results: Hatched and reared by Wendy then hand-reared. Result of AI on 10/2/09
comments:
Pearl's third egg of three hatched by Wendy, then hand-reared following poor weight gain from 12 days. Referred to as Pearl3 during hand-rearing, then Katie (Richard Henry's friend) initially on Anchor, until official naming. Named Jemma by Mark Carwardine (BBC presenter Last Chance to See documentary - follows up Mark & Douglas Adams original radio series & book orduced 20 years earlier) - after the daughter of a good friend. She’s only eight years-old and has already developed a passion for wildlife and conservation. It is a great step in ensuring that the Kakapo conservation story is passed on to the next generation. Also meaning gem or jewel - which are obviously precious - as is the Kakapo. Pearl was artificially inseminated with sperm from Stumpy following mating with Felix; Stumpy is Jemma’s father. Plumage: olive head, but faded grey-green body plumage like Nora.

Died from suspected aspergillosis at Dunedin Wildlife Hospital. DETAILS and CORRECT TIME need adding.

Suzanne's 3rd chick from 3 eggs in 2016. Hatched with Suzanne, but transferred to Margaret Maree's nest at 7 days when the nest, chick & mum became very wet. Removed from MM's nest at 13 days for hand-rearing & treatment due to star-gazing (torticollis; with undetermined cause), which she gradually recovered from. Chick name 3-3-16 also referred to as Star and Matariki during hand-rearing. Sudden demise after weaning in pen on Anchor Island and died aged 118 days. PM: Good condition. Enlarged liver/spleen. Left lung red/purple with areas of consolidation. Histology: Severe mycotic pneumonia. Normal liver lead & zinc. Lung negative for chlamydia PCR. Negative faecal parasitology. Lactobacillus & E. coli in liver & lung (secondary). No fungi isolated. Diagnosis fungal pneumonia.
